description:
The R pipeline for scrub typhus diagnostic research employs an automated, innovative approach using Bayesian latent class analysis to evaluate the performance of ELISA and PCR tests without a gold standard reference. Utilizing a Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) method via JAGS, it calculates key diagnostic metrics such as sensitivity, specificity, and predictive values, complete with credible intervals.&nbsp; 
 Key features of the pipeline include the automatic generation of publication-ready outputs, such as Word reports and various figure formats, which streamline the reporting process. It consists of four modules that assess diagnostic accuracy, analyze patient demographics with confidence intervals, cluster symptoms through multiple correspondence analysis, and explore symptom-demographic associations using Fisher's exact tests. 
 The pipeline is designed with robust error handling to preserve results during failures, timestamped logs for audit trails, and a modular architecture that allows for both independent and coordinated script execution. It ensures reproducibility through automated documentation and standardized file organization. This framework addresses the challenges in scrub typhus diagnostics, providing a rigorous Bayesian.&nbsp;

